News - Date: 10 June 2017Written by: Kaizer Nengovhela / Viewed: 155A group of angry women from Madombidzha protested outside the Louis Trichardt Magistrate&rsquo;s Court on Wednesday, demanding that the court not grant bail to a murder suspect.In April, the lifeless body of a young woman, Jennifer Netshivhangani, was discovered near the Schoemansdal Station with a wound to the head. The police&#39;s investigations led to the arrest of her boyfriend, Stephen Matshikhiri, who was last seen with the deceased.Representing the women&nbsp;who were picketing, Ms Mapula Raphebele said they would oppose bail. &ldquo;We have had enough of endless, brutal and senseless murders within our communities,&rdquo; she added. &ldquo;Our young ones do not deserve to die like rats.&rdquo;She added that they had&nbsp;decided to march to show society that they&nbsp;say no to the killing of women. &ldquo;We went there to make a statement that all killers belong in prison. We abide by the law, which dictates that one remains innocent until proven otherwise by a court of law,&rdquo; she added.The case was postponed to 17 July for a bail application. The protesters later dispersed peacefully to their different homes.Women protesting at the Louis Trichardt Magistrate&#39;s Court.Kaizer Nengovhela started writing stories for Limpopo Mirror more than a decade ago, in 2 000. Prior to that he had a five year stint at Phala-Phala FM as sports presenter. In 2005 Kaizer received an award from the province&#39;s premier as Best Sports Presenter. The same year he was also nominated as Best Sports Reporter by the Makhado Municipality. Kaizer was awarded the Mathatha Tsedu award in 2014.Email: kaizerdo@webmail.co.za